<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; VIDEO; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  (box) Mo' Better Blues  Writer/director Spike Lee's cliche-ridden but
enjoyable story of a jazz musician (Denzel Washington) obsessed by his music
and indecisive about his women. Recommended. (MCA; rated R. Due Thursday.); 
(box) Young Guns II  Emilio Estevez and Kiefer Sutherland in a sequel to the
popular rock 'n roll Western; here, Billy the Kid escapes jail and is tracked
by lawman Pat Garrett. (CBS/Fox; R. Due Thursday.);  (box) At Sword's Point
(1951)  The sons of the Three Musketeers rally to the aid of their queen in
this swashbuckler starring Cornel Wilde and Maureen O'Hara. (Turner)  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MOVIE
CAPSULES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  NEW; RELEASES  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   (box) Bachelor Apartment (1931)  Irene Dunne in an early romantic comedy.
(Turner);  (box) Berlin Express (1948)  Political suspense flick about
international police guarding a German VIP on a train. (Turner);  (box) Born
to be Bad (1950)  m Joan Fontaine is an evil woman, married to a rich man but
carrying on with a writer. Tsk, tsk. (Turner);  (box) Sister Kenny (1946) 
Rosalind Russell portrays the nurse who developed a radical polio treatment.
(Turner);  (box) Tom, Dick and Harry (1940)  Romantic comedy in which Ginger
Rogers daydreams about her three boyfriends. (Turner);  (box) Beauty for the
Asking (1939)  Lucille Ball is a player in this soaper about jealous women in
a cosmetics store. (Turner);  (box) What Price Hollywood? (1932)  Interesting
mainly as the basis for "A Star is Born," and for its behind-the-scenes
glimpses of early talkie production. (Turner);  (box) Without Reservations
(1946)  Claudette Colbert and John Wayne in a semi-wild romantic comedy. She's
a writer on a train to Hollywood; he's a marine she thinks would be the
perfect lead for her movie. (Turner);  (box) A Woman's Secret (1949)  Maureen
O'Hara in a film noir about a singer and his evil successor. (Turner); 
MISCELLANEOUS; (box) War Requiem  Powerful anti-war film by Derek Jarman,
featuring a graphic montage of 20th century war footage set to composer
Benjamin Britten's celebrated oratorio. (Mystic Fire);  (box) The Turtles:
Happy Together  In-depth videography of the wacky '60s group, including "promo
films" (primitive music videos) of their early hits. (Rhino);  (box) Todd
Rundgren: Live in Japan  99-minute filmed concert including hits like "Hello
It's Me." (Rhino);  (box) Shoot News: Make Money With Your Camcorder 
30-minute instructional entry which covers how to find, tape and market news.
As if we need any more news! (Pentrex);  (box) The H-Bomb and Other Smash Hits
 Compilation of propaganda films from the '50s explaining civil defense and
the H-bomb threat. (Video Yesteryear)  </TEXT>
